textDisplay: This was a good video. Some of the ideas here, there are points one could have made that might've made the video... a bit less conclusive, but perhaps a bit more well rounded in its message. To name a few things in these categories, I'm not sure I agree that dynamic obselecence, or the evolution of style and aesthetic that renders older styles less popular, is just some man-made ploy to tell more cars, more clothes. Obviously it's part of the market, but our tastes change whether someone's there to capitalize off of it or not, and often style and technology are more entwined than they seem. Also, it should be mentioned that at the end of "The Man in the White Suit," the suit falls apart because the polymers in it decomposed, although he goes off to assumedly try again at the formula. Kind of an important part of the film, it leads to further interpretation, but it would force the overal message of the video to be a little less certain of one answer to the probelm of designed obselecence. None of those things really make the video bad in any way, but it's something to consider when discussing the topic, I dunno, might interest someone. That being said, in terms of the art of documentary, I really enjoyed this, it was entertaining.

textDisplay:
When you think about it, the multiple cells including itself or not itself resolves pretty easily down to both.
On each and every scale it's separated.
To put it simply:
Each of these things we study are essentially just the words we name them with. If I'm looking at a cell, it's still a cell, on that constant spectrum of existence.
Each of those cells acts as it's own body. Just as the pieces making it up divided further, act as their own body.
These things we look at exist operate, and navigate, through some sensory system to manage resources. They also exist on scales so small our words could, if honed, effect their very nature. Or, for that matter, entirely not effect them.
You can test this as easily as with a conversation.

LEDs are planned obsolete through the AC/DC converter inside. The LED element will be fine, but the converter blows after some number of hours and the bulb needs to be replaced.

textDisplay:
I see so many things being thrown away for no apparent reason. I once found some expensive home sandals in our house's trash that had some ripped off orthopedic stuff at the heels, other than that brand new. I wear those now as my heels cover the "messy" part anyway and no cussioning or whatever was lost.
But same goes for smartphones: my banking app didn't support below Android 7 anymore (I think that's fair due to security reasons?), but since my old Android 6 phone still works fine for me I needed a solution. Samsung in my case doesn't support A7 on that Samsung 5 Neo device. So I quickly learned how to install a third party OS that would simulate Android 10 and hoped for the best: works fine, is super fast again and totally slim. Took me two hours, saved me from buying a new phone.
Same for smaller household gadgets like my 50y old Espresso machine that looks super expensive (that it was not initially) or water heater: some super basic soldering and voilá all electrics fine again. Is my Espresso machine able to spit out 10 different kinds of coffee by me sliding on a touchscreen? No. Does it create the base products for every ...-ccino (espresso and steamed milk)? Yes.
Oh, does that mean you have to invest a little bit of time to make one and actually develop some skills? Totally. Do you enjoy the process and the final product every day? Yessir. Are guests impressed to be served a manual product? Almost always. By the way: the water heater does its job, too: it heats water.

I think what the average joe needs to be able to do: basic soldering, the bare minimum amount of knowledge about electrics (literally no more than "which wire goes where"), basic woodworking (drilling, honing, grinding/sanding), basic metalworking (same as before, if possible welding, though that can be dangerous without experience), some basic understanding how software works and the ability to search and follow tutorials on the internet and most important: the willingness to repair FIRST before finally giving up on a product. By the way: before you throw it away, put it on ebay for 0€/$ and someone WILL pick it up (for repair or spare parts).

textDisplay:
What I find interesting, as well, is that in the world of arcade rhythm games (Dance Dance Revolution, Pump it Up, etc.), new versions of the game with updated songs would release every year or two for arcades to purchase. DDR has had 26 arcade releases since 1998, yet it's one of the simplest games out there. Why not just update the songs and let owners use one machine?

A new rhythm game, very similar to DDR, called StepManiaX, based on a 2011 freeware called StepMania 5.1, aims to change this, by providing one game version with constant internet updates and high quality, easily repairable hardware, all for an even lower price than competitors. It's essentially set up to destroy modern DDR in the west, and I'm welcoming of this. StepManiaX is my kind of arcade game model, and I wish it well.

textDisplay: I have to disagree with the final premise that the only good reason for obsolescence is technical improvement.  That thought doesn't mesh with the human mind or economics.  GM may have used color and style to keep people buying new cars, but they also advances the technology slightly with each iteration. If people weren't compelled to buy the new product buy emotion GM wouldn't have had the capital needed for R&D. This would have caused tech to stagnate.  Luckily GM and the other car companies were able to compelled people to keep re investing in cars.  Modern cars are basically spaceships compared to the cars of the 50s.  They are hundreds of times safer, less polluting, and more efficient.  Not all thanks to the car companies them selfs but you get the idea.  If you want to see a counterpoint. The general aviation market is dieing due to lack of obsolescence. A cessna 172 has been the same basic plane for 50 years and because non presuresed planes are infinitely repairable, people aren't buying new ones. This is causing prices for new planes to skyrocket due to low production volumes, which intern is killing demand, which is then killing innovation.  No system is perfect but without a life expectancy the manufacturing volume required to innovate dies. This is why a circular economy is such a tempting idea.

textDisplay: The luddite idea that new technology makes jobs obsolete is true on an industry-by-industry or worker-by-worker basis... sometimes you're a skilled worker making a good income but then something changes and your skills are now worthless, which sucks! However, it's just not true on a societal level.  There's a version of this called the Broken Window Fallacy, in which mischievous children promote economic growth by throwing rocks through windows (thus keeping glass makers in business). What it forgets is that money that is now being spent on needless or preventable tasks is money that could have been spent on more useful things, which is better for the consumer but also still keeps someone in work. It's pretty rare for technology to reduce the amount of labour needed and much more common for it to mean that we stop spending money on one kind of labour and instead spend that money on some other kind of labour instead. Even in situations where technology means that a person's labour can do two or three times as much work, we typically end up producing and buying more rather than reducing the amount of labour spent on working (with today's technology, we could all work one day a week if we were content to merely replicate the living standards of our ancestors... but that would suck).

textDisplay: I have a friend who worked in some government labs, and practically all the old oscilloscopes, power meters, etc. which you could consider "high tech" during those times, came complete with all circuit diagrams and stuff. He could repair, on his own, something as complex as an oscilloscope, because they told you down to the value of the smallest resistor where it had to go and what was its operational purpose. You had even the troubleshooting manual with what to measure and test to verify that it was fixed. Then they started denying the user that information, given only to certified repair shops and technicians, until everything went down to chips and not even the technicians had anything that they could repair anymore. You had to buy the whole new thing, or pay exorbitantly for repairs directly by the manufacturer. There was a curve tracer which had these soft rubber touch buttons, like the ones in calculators that have this carbon contact thing in the back to complete the circuit, which were already worn out after so many years of use. We contacted the company to ask how much was the repair, and they said that it was around $2500... I went online looking for those generic buttons and bought a small pack of like 60 of them for $10, the exact same ones used by the instrument. We opened the thing, changed the rubber buttons, and that was it. Didn't take even 20 minutes to do. $2500 MY ASS. And all these companies now do the same thing.

textDisplay: 9:03 I was helping someone write a course about product design, sustainability, and eco-efficiency and a lot of it had to do with metering the expected 'service of a product and being able to retrieve the components as part of the product lifecycle. That is: say you were manufacturing carpet. You want the product to be sustainable, made of eco-efficient materials (easily repurposed or refurbished and so much so that it CONTRIBUTES to the environment), energy-efficient, profitable, and made with a supply chain that also follows these guidelines. You would create carpet that cost the same as existing products, give a life expectancy (say 10 years), then retrieve the byproduct efficiently with zero-net ecological impact (the real goal is positive). The materials could then be retrieved, eliminating waste as fully recyclable, and used to evolve into new carpeting or other positive byproducts. Who wants carpet to last forever anyway? But this is the next generation of product evolution. Determine life-service and build all components to be sustainable without waste. The latter is the real issue. Why have a disposable coffee cup whose service time is under 1 hour last hundreds of years? That's just poor design.

textDisplay:
12:45 Actually, Ford vehicles were available in a variety of colors from the very start---gray, green, blue, and red.
Incidentally, black was NOT available in the earliest Ford vehicles. (rendering it less than likely that Henry Ford ever said those words which have been so long ascribed to him, as black was not even an option for five years)
Why? Expense. The only way to get colors back then (as there were no chemical colors...not like we have now)was to use pigments in white paint. The darker the color, the more pigment used and thus the more expensive the paint was to make.
Fun fact: For about 100 years, black replaced purple as the color most favored by the wealthy for that exact reason: it was more expensive.

textDisplay:
Hi. Hardware engineer here. In order to make a battery easily replaceable would mean sacrificing performance, form factor, and size. Consumers are simply unwilling to accept that. That's why there are basically no mainstream phones on the market with easily replaceable batteries. I personally had the last mainstream phone with one, a Galaxy Note 4, and I would literally get made fun of for how big it was.

Does it suck that batteries don't last forever? Sure, but people vote with their dollars and they definitely vote in favor of smaller devices with harder to replace batteries.

It is not planned obsolescence, it is anticipated product lifetime. Theres a difference. You guys don't say this stuff when talking about other devices. When a car breaks down after 300k miles you don't call it "planned obsolescence" you just say the cars at the end of its life.

That being said, the real problem here is apple intentionally making it harder to repair their devices. That is absurd and actually much worse than planned obsolescence.
textOriginal:

Does it suck that batteries don't last forever? Sure, but people vote with their dollars and they definitely vote in favor of smaller devices with harder to replace batteries. 

It is *not* planned obsolescence,  it is anticipated product lifetime. Theres a difference.  You guys don't say this stuff when talking about other devices. When a car breaks down after 300k miles you don't call it "planned obsolescence" you just say the cars at the end of its life.

That being said, the real problem here is apple intentionally making it harder to repair their devices. That is absurd and actually much worse than planned obsolescence.

textDisplay: You forgot to caveat the "reached the point of an everlasting lightbulb" LEDs only last as long as you're painting it (selling a house before buying a replacement bulb) is only true under very optimal conditions. For example, leaving it on permanently is not going to work for most LEDs. But firing the switch too often also reduces life. Humid regions or even particularly humid houses will fair less well than others. There are many factors that still result in end of life for a particular led, although they can be made more tightly enclosed with higher grade heat dissipating parts, etc. Stating it like you did at the end makes it seem like there's no where to progress on the LED bulb, but there definitely are ways to improve it. Untapped, but not undiscovered.
textOriginal: You forgot to caveat the "reached the point of an everlasting lightbulb" LEDs only last as long as you're painting it (selling a house before buying a replacement bulb) is only true under very optimal conditions. textDisplay:
You know, I'm really grateful that you pointed this out, because most people I've interacted with don't seem willing to believe that greed would be a powerful enough force to do something like this.

With this conspiracy in mind--including the lies told to cover it up--you'd think people might start asking whether other similar agreements have been made (and may continue to be made), like the iPod issue.

The funny thing about conspiracies is that it's not always just "a cooky conspiracy."

P.S. I've yet to have an LED lightbulb last anywhere near as long as the package says it should.

Even if there were to be warranty claims, the cost is so low it doesn't matter anyway. Many second generation LED bulbs with their bulky metal heat sinks are still running just fine 8 years later.

textDisplay: Being a vintage / collectable electronic dealer I disagree with this video. I mean most of my income is from selling old electronic or consumer devices, Walkmans, HiFis, cameras, radios. A lot of them last significantly longer than people would have assumed, even without replacement parts. I had some USB 1.0 sound cards that, not even they're still usable nowadays after 20 more years, but the latest Windows still recognize them and the default driver still works on them, of course the sound quality still good in today's standard. I know some companies would do 'planned obsolescence', namely Apple; but in fact, that's not as common as people would think. Even under heavy usage, with proper care and maintenance, a lot of consumer products can last a good long time. I think it's more of a cultural thing that people want to throw away things and find an excuse to say they don't last, or just buying cheap stuff and wouldn't care about the quality. Another point I want to make is, 'planned obsolescence' is actually harder to design than making it last longer, only companies with/earn a lot of money would do that. I mean unless you make a timer inside the device, let it breaks at the time you want is a lot harder than let it last. Also, there are few things that are not really 'planned obsolescence' but people tend to include:1) pure low quality, they break down easily and randomly. 2) end of support, like drivers, updates or maintenance parts are no longer available, and 3) out of fashion, like you don't use the camcorder anymore because your cellphone can do the same job better. Excludes all these points and still make the product 'planned obsolescence' would really mean a lot of engineering effort has been put into the product, and nowadays not even Apple would do this.

textDisplay: Technological obsolescence Is the bane of our existence today. Nothing is repaired any longer. It's all component replacement and waste because everything has it's own computer controller it ether costs 1000% more to replace or they simply quit making it so there is no such thing as a replacement.  A perfect example is a windshield wiper/washer motor. There used to be a wire going from the battery positive to a simple switch then to the motor then the motor to ground. Then they came up with variable speed capable motors and switches sending different voltages to attain high low or intermittent. But now, they still run it all the same  Except power from the switch is low signal voltage and instead they run the high voltage to the motor with relays and a computer controller in the motor. Now that $30 dollar motor is $600 because of the electronic and you can't just use any switch or any motor. If the technology become obsolete and you still want the option to function. You either need to learn how to diagnose and repair circuit boards or pay someone to do it. Or you have to entirely redesign it to work with new wiring and components like they used to or you are screw. And OMG if you start running into problems with the the signal voltage wiring. Technology, technological obsolescence and insane costs are forcing still good components to be thrown away or recycled a decade or more early. I bought a 1953 caterpillar grader. No hydraulics, computer chips, nothing. It's all operated by levers running gears. and electrical is all standard. There is nothing I can not fix on that machine. With some tools and the knowledge I gained working and repairing on the farm. With a small equipped shop I can literally not just repair but make the replacement parts. If you figure that modern graders might have a 20 year lifespan before general wear and tear combined technological obsolescence make the new grader obsolete My old 53 grader is about to start it's fifth life time of use in 2023. I just built 3 road with it last year. And now the Brand spanky new stuff is real bad because many new heavy equipment manufacturers now use electronic play station like controllers to run major can't do without functions like steering. It's no longer just luxury accessories you can operate without. They are doing this to main absolutely essential operations that the equipment has to be able to accomplish to operate. Technology is creating insane amount of garbage. Gone are the days where bearings or brushes go. You take out screws replace the part then it's good for another 15 or 20 years. Now the whole unit ends up in the dump because a 20 cent chip or a tiny capacitor blew. All Dump grounds have got Tons of garbage appliances for this exact reason. Control board went under warranty then again after and you are just sick of dealing with it so too the dump it goes. As for the led lights. Ya. dream on! They won't outlast your house. They last longer but the highly inflated cost shows you how long they should last. But, you rarely get that.

textDisplay:
This video dances around the political side of economics and capitalism. Have companies compete and you get convergence on what is desired by the "democracy" of buyers. Socialism is a tool of the masses to get redistribution of goods or services that they were either unable to acquire, or had to choose between lesser options. I think the honest approach is understanding that cycles happen everywhere and we need to appreciate both capitalist and socialist "mechanisms" of progressing through time. I'm a true centrist but also a controls freak lol. I'd appreciate it if people didn't pick ideological sides and were just more honest with the approaches and how the trade off's might be worth arguing. Socialism gives more people health care, but cancer research could grind to a halt. With the idea that wealth is not fixed, but generated by supply, you can be flexible in different industries to find peak distribution AND innovation. The balance in hard, convincing people to stop applying their ideals in one understanding to everything else they are less knowledgeable about... impossible. Or so it seems.
Thanks for doing this video. It's a beautifully subtle way of explaining how good and desirable engineers are ;)

textDisplay: Great video, but a typical LED "Bulb" is NOT everlasting.  Claims of 50,000 hours? I've replaced plenty already. but why? is it cheap components? or planning, my guess is that the mass produced circuit boards, "guts" that drive the actual led are the weak point. Sure, the change over from inc. to led had a cost, but I'd imagine that the electrical savings is a by product and gimmick to price the bulb higher, I'd like to see this same examination comparing the actual cost/lifespan etc of incandescent v. LED.  The thing I appreciate about an LED, is that they give off so much less heat, and in an air conditioned enviornment, any input from a bulb has to be balanced by hvac.  Who actually can make that calculation, when a leaky window, or leaving the door open while bringing in groceries likely makes a bigger deficit.

textDisplay:
I don't like people saying "obsolescence" when they mean a physical life span.
I'm not really mad at IT products being better and better over time making you want to replace the "not so-old stuff", I'm mad when they are being forced out by programmed mechanical failure or by the drop of support or overpriced support and repair.

For some products, a limited life-span can make sense for the customer : you have something that acts like a fuse so that the product doesn't fail later on by catching fire or by having that saw blade fly away at high speed or whatever. The failure is programmed so that it is a safe failure. This is of course not why most products are programmed to fail.

I'm not really mad at IT products being better and better over time making you want to replace the "not so-old stuff", I'm mad when they are being forced out by programmed mechanical failure or by the drop of support or overpriced support and repair.

For some products, a limited life-span can make sense for the customer : you have something that acts like a fuse so that the product doesn't fail later on by catching fire or by having that saw blade fly away at high speed or whatever. The failure is programmed so that it is a safe failure. This is of course not why most products are programmed to fail.

textDisplay:
Beyond the right to repair, it's the right to buy things that lasts.
Now, it's true that it could impact the work force but we will have to get there eventually for ecological reasons if nothing else.

One way to help achieve this is to better inform the consumer about the longevity of things but that is quite limited.
I believe that in the end, non-profit groups have to take a major role and that typically means government agencies.
Those agencies can establish what the longevity of certain products could/should be and rules can be made to encourage that longevity; for instance by taxing products that do not last or forcing a labelling on companies that make shorter lived products.
And if that isn't enough, then new companies financed and controlled by non-profit organizations can enter the market with long-lasting products.
textOriginal:
Beyond the right to repair, it's the right to buy things that lasts.
Now, it's true that it could impact the work force but we will have to get there eventually for ecological reasons if nothing else.

One way to help achieve this is to better inform the consumer about the longevity of things but that is quite limited.
I believe that in the end, non-profit groups have to take a major role and that typically means government agencies.
Those agencies can establish what the longevity of certain products could/should be and rules can be made to encourage that longevity; for instance by taxing products that do not last or forcing a labelling on companies that make shorter lived products.
And if that isn't enough, then new companies financed and controlled by non-profit organizations can enter the market with long-lasting products.

textDisplay: We had a similar lightbulb in the back room at Firehouse Engine 5 where the horses once staged. When I arrived it had become Engine 8 "On The Avenue" and that stable became a utility room, the hay loft above was now a exercise/workout room. But the lightbulb remained, still burning. The firehouse celebrated 100 years since it was built and the time capsule was removed from the cornerstone. The contents were reviewed and I happened to be there when the newspaper was there and I was photographed with one other coworker looking at the contents, and they published it, with our names included, (they even spelled my name correctly) and that printed edition with the story and our picture in color was placed in the time capsule and once again, placed into the cornerstone and mortared in for another 100 years.  I won't be there when they open it next time, but the lightbulb might still be there.

textDisplay:
There is a major economic problem here, not a physics problem. The assumption you're implicitly making is that the only reason a bulb must be replaced is by burnout. If producers made bulbs that never burned out, they would be far, far more expensive. The cost-to-replace those bulbs would be much higher, in the event they were broken by, say, a young child swinging a toy around (actually has happened in my household, multiple times).

The cost-benefit analysis was made iteratively by the market several billions times and the product evolved to a far lower cost bulb that will burn out quicker. It is not a mistake or a conspiracy; it is a selective pressure with a major comparative advantage.
textOriginal:
There is a major economic problem here, not a physics problem.  The assumption you're implicitly making is that the only reason a bulb must be replaced is by burnout.  If producers made bulbs that never burned out, they would be far, far more expensive.  The cost-to-replace those bulbs would be much higher, in the event they were broken by, say, a young child swinging a toy around (actually has happened in my household, multiple times).  

The cost-benefit analysis was made iteratively by the market several billions times and the product evolved to a far lower cost bulb that will burn out quicker.  It is not a mistake or a conspiracy; it is a selective pressure with a major comparative advantage.

I seriously want to know which appliances / products are supposed to fail after 3 years, as many people claim. All devices I own, except my Smartphone, which I broke because I dropped it and for which an repair wasn't making any sense anymore, and an electric shaver, were you can't change the blades and which only cost 15€, are at least 5 years old. Most of my clothes are over 3 years old, some even 10 years. They don't look brand-new, but still fine and orderly.

The only things which failed before an acceptable time was the motherboard of my PC after 4 years, although it was an good brand. That probably was just bad luck. And an brand-shirt, where the brand seemingly went the fast-fashion-way since I last bought one around 7 years ago, which I still wear regulary. I needed to buy shoes every year; I even tried really expensive sneakers. I then bought leather shoes for 60€ and still wear them daily since 4 years. Now they don't look that nice anymore, as I did everything in them, and will soon buy new "sunday shoes". When my financial situation will allow that again, as it was hit by an 2000€ repair bill for my car, which is 26 years old, by the way. Most people seem to buy the cheapest crap, or repeatadly expensive low-quality things, and wonder, why nothing lasts, and never avoid brands if they made bad experiences with them or other people did.

With Brands I don't mean expensive things. You can't build an decent electric shaver for 20€. You need to pay 50€ if you want one that will last and one were you can change the blades every 2-3 years and were the blades will still be available in 10-15 years. You can't buy pants for 10€ and expect them to last, they will cost around 30€. An T-Shirt can cost 10€, an shirt 20€. The exceptions always are real clearance-deals, not the false-advertising ones. But then these things will last for an very long time and you will save a lot of money in the long run. Every two years I spend around 150€ on clothes, of which only 100€ are really necessary. That is almost nothing compared to other regular expenses, such as food, eating/drinking out, fuel, heating, entertainment expenses, like video games, the cinema or streaming services or electricity. If I can afford these things with an total budget of 1000€ per month, of which around 350€ need to be substracted for rent and energy expenses, and another 150€ per month for my weekly bar evening, this is possible for the average person in other industrialized, rich countries as well.
textOriginal:
I seriously want to know which appliances / products are supposed to fail after 3 years, as many people claim. All devices I own, except my Smartphone, which I broke because I dropped it and for which an repair wasn't making any sense anymore, and an electric shaver, were you can't change the blades and which only cost 15€, are at least 5 years old. Most of my clothes are over 3 years old, some even 10 years. They don't look brand-new, but still fine and orderly.

The only things which failed before an acceptable time was the motherboard of my PC after 4 years, although it was an good brand. That probably was just bad luck. And an brand-shirt, where the brand seemingly went the fast-fashion-way since I last bought one around 7 years ago, which I still wear regulary. I needed to buy shoes every year; I even tried really expensive sneakers. I then bought leather shoes for 60€ and still wear them daily since 4 years. textDisplay:
planned obsolescence & legacy auto's practice of changing body styles to coax buyers into 'next year's model'... does play to the vanity of consumers. as they change the body style every 3 or 4 years... it lets consumers look on & say- oh.. you're not driving the 'current model'. nothing but pure appeal to our vanity. I suppose it works well enough. or does it? then legacy auto tells us that they build vehicles to last the space of 100k miles because 'that's what consumers want'... I call BS. in 1963 chevrolet made a car called the belair. it had a 283 v8 coupled to a manual 3 speed transmission with an automatic overdrive- effectively giving it a 6 speed transmission. this combo gave the car 25mpg. if 'babied' along & oil changed with regular maintenance- this car could reach 1 million miles. buy a chevrolet today... you'd be lucky to get 160k miles out of it.... and we're told by legacy auto that's "what we want".

then along comes tesla with cars that ROUTINELY go 400-500k miles, don't burn gas, don't need oil changes or pretty much any other kind of maintenance and OH! don't need smog checks or catalytic converters! to add insult to injury... tesla designed a great body style... and that style has REMAINED UNCHANGED since the start. THE NERVER OF THEM! and to the shock of 'stock analysts, 'car magazines', msnbc, jim chanos and the other long standing line of oil shills short selling tesla and publishing tesla fudd stories... tesla is the most popular, fastest growing brand ON THE PLANET. it seems the consumer has spoken. it seems we really don't need our car's looks to change every couple years. it seems we really do like it when... our cars LAST LONG... if for no other reason than- it increases resale value.

this lesson is one that big corporate (by majority) simply can't seem to learn. maximizing profits through a lens that only looks at the next 6 months... has a MASSIVE downfall. it only takes ONE company with ONE guy at the helm like elon musk... and your planned obsolescence just relegated your entire company into the trash heap. eg- Boeing vs. SpaceX.

it's not so much a conspiracy per say... as it is simple mis-management of corporate assets. they've forgotten the FIRST rule of business: GIVE THE CUSTOMER WHAT THEY WANT. that doesn't mean try to MANIPULATE THEM into believing what YOU WANT.

Ask yourself this one simple question: when was the last time we heard the ceo of ANY auto manufacturer say "our goal is to build a car that will last for ONE MILLION MILES"? OMG! they'd fire him! maybe even BEHEAD HIM! but that's PRECISELY what tesla & elon plan to do- and WILL accomplish with their 4680 cells. one car- one lifetime. and why not? if the goal is to make LESS pollution.. then we should strive not only to make the car pollute less.. but to make it last longer so that we don't need the pollution of making another one every few years. DUHH!

textDisplay:
So, they reduce the lifespan to products so that the factory workers which produce them can keep their jobs as there will always be a large demand. Which in turn requires those very same workers to endlessly replace their possessions every few years. So now the worker has to work harder and take overtime to afford a later version of what just wore down, pushing the people into a recession by increasing the cost of living. With the increased cost of living, it is now imperative that the worker continues to retain their job, just to put food and replacements on the table. So yes, the worker continues to be employed, but now the companies drive the necessity of it. As demand for the resources to produce the product rises; the cost jumps up as resources and sustainability dwindle. Now the replacement item costs more for the worker until it reaches the point in which they can no longer afford it without sacrifice. The repression becomes depression, which puts the worker out of work.

Who benefits from this backwards decision?

textDisplay: More than simply shortening a devices lifespan, engineered obsolescence is often about increasing the precision of expiration. When you place components with known durability in series you reduce the devices overall duration, but more importantly you dramatically reduce the window in which you can expect the device to fail. This lets you sell warranties or guarantees that will reliably not need to be paid off.
textOriginal: More than simply shortening a devices lifespan, engineered obsolescence is often about increasing the precision of expiration. When you place components with known durability in series you reduce the devices overall duration, but more importantly you dramatically reduce the window in which you can expect the device to fail. This lets you sell warranties or guarantees that will reliably not need to be paid off.

textDisplay:
Well that last section was way off - LED bulbs DON'T last 10-15 years, and are still built with obsolescence by design. Just read up on the 'Dubai bulb' Philips made - literally designed to last a massively long time, and to be far more energy efficient. How? Simple - more LEDs in each bulb, but run at a lower power. That's a REALLY simple step, yet light bulb manufacturers around the world won't implement it, regardless of how much more ecologically sound it is (more efficient, less physical waste).

Those of us outside of Dubai can't buy this bulb, as Philips signed a multi-million dollar, multi-year exclusivity deal with Dubai, so it can ONLY be (legally) bought in Dubai. And those multiple millions are the only reason it exists at all. A lifetime lasting, energy saving, ecological bulb exists, and can be reproduced without any major issue by every bulb manufacturer. But manufacturers won't make it without millions of dollars upfront.
